SIMPLE: mockery
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mockery
<hw>Mock"er*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Mockeries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F.
<ets>moquerie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of mocking,
deriding, and exposing to contempt, by mimicry, by insincere imitation,
or by a false show of earnestness; a counterfeit appearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is, as the air, invulnerable,⟦br⟧
And our vain blows malicious <qex>mockery</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Grace at meals is now generally so performed as to look more like
a <qex>mockery</qex> upon devotion than any solemn application of the
mind to God.</q> <rj><qau>Law.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And bear about the <qex>mockery</qex> of woe.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Insulting or contemptuous action or speech;
contemptuous merriment; derision; ridicule.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The laughingstock of fortune's <qex>mockeries</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Subject of laughter, derision, or sport.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The cruel handling of the city whereof they made a
<qex>mockery</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>2 Macc. viii. 17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mocking</ent>⟦br⟧
